  "prompt": "What are the fundamental rights in Russia?",
  "response": "In Russia, the fundamental rights of citizens are enshrined in the Constitution of the Russian Federation, adopted in 1993. These rights are guaranteed by the state and reflect principles of democracy, rule of law, and human dignity. The fundamental rights in Russia include:\n\n### **1. Civil and Political Rights**\n   - **Right to Life** (Article 20): Every individual has the right to life.\n   - **Right to Liberty and Personal Security** (Article 22): No one may be detained or arrested without lawful grounds.\n   - **Right to Equality** (Article 19): All citizens are equal before the law and have equal rights regardless of race, gender, religion, or other distinctions.\n   - **Freedom of Speech and Expression** (Article 29): Citizens have the right to freely express their opinions and beliefs.\n   - **Freedom of Assembly** (Article 31): Citizens have the right to peacefully assemble and hold demonstrations.\n   - **Freedom of Association** (Article 30): Citizens have the right to form associations, including political parties and trade unions.\n   - **Right to Participate in Governance** (Article 32): Citizens have the right to vote, be elected, and participate in public affairs.\n\n### **2. Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights**\n   - **Right to Work** (Article 37): Citizens have the right to freely choose their profession and enjoy fair working conditions.\n   - **Right to Education** (Article 43): Everyone has the right to education, and basic education is free and compulsory.\n   - **Right to Health Care** (Article 41): Citizens have the right to health care and medical assistance, provided by the state.\n   - **Right to Housing** (Article 40): Citizens have the right to housing, and the state promotes access to housing.\n   - **Right to Social Security** (Article 39): Citizens are entitled to social security in cases of old age, illness, or disability.\n\n### **3. Judicial and Legal Rights**\n   - **Right to a Fair Trial** (Article 46): Everyone has the right to judicial protection and a fair trial.\n   - **Presumption of Innocence** (Article 49): No one may be considered guilty of a crime until proven in court.\n   - **Right to Legal Assistance** (Article 48): Citizens have the right to legal counsel, including free legal aid in certain cases.\n   - **Protection from Torture and Inhuman Treatment** (Article 21): No one may be subjected to torture, violence, or degrading treatment.\n\n### **4. Environmental and Cultural Rights**\n   - **Right to a Healthy Environment** (Article 42): Citizens have the right to a healthy environment and access to information about environmental conditions.\n   - **Right to Cultural and Creative Development** (Article 44): Citizens have the right to participate in cultural life and protect their cultural heritage.\n\n### **5. Limitations on Rights**\n   - While the Constitution guarantees these rights, it also allows for certain limitations. For example, rights may be restricted to protect national security, public order, or the rights of others. However, such restrictions must be proportionate and comply with the law.\n\n### **6. Enforcement of Rights**\n   - The Constitutional Court of the Russian Federation oversees the enforcement of constitutional rights and resolves disputes related to constitutional compliance.\n   - Citizens may appeal to courts or international bodies if their rights are violated.\n\nThese fundamental rights form the basis of the legal and social system in Russia, although their implementation and enforcement can sometimes be subject to criticism and debate.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
